Class CoreSpeedSet

java.lang.Object
java.util.AbstractCollection<CoreSpeed>
java.util.AbstractList<CoreSpeed>
java.util.Vector<CoreSpeed>
WorkLoadSet.CoreSpeedSet
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<CoreSpeed>, Collection<CoreSpeed>, List<CoreSpeed>, RandomAccess, SequencedCollection<CoreSpeed>
public class CoreSpeedSet extends Vector<CoreSpeed>
Collection of DVFS (Dynamic Voltage and Frequency Scaling) operating points for a core group. Extends Vector to maintain an ordered list of CoreSpeed entries sorted by ascending speed.

The first element (index 0) represents the idle operating point (returned by getIDELSpeed()), the second (index 1) represents the minimum active speed (getMinSpeed()). The last element represents the maximum speed (getMaxSpeed()). Convenience accessors expose raw speed values and frequency boundaries. Selection logic in getCurrentSpeed(double) integrates the parent core set's ideal/non-ideal model flag: ideal mode clamps continuously within min/max; non-ideal mode snaps upward to the next defined discrete speed (ceiling) or to max if above.

Author:
ShiuJia

    • getCurrentSpeed

      public double getCurrentSpeed(double s)
      Select or clamp a target speed according to the parent's ideal flag.

      Ideal mode: returns continuous value clamped to [minFrequency, maxFrequency]. Non-ideal mode: if above max returns max; otherwise returns the first discrete DVFS step whose speed is >= target (ceil); if none found returns 0. (Returning 0 indicates an unexpected empty set or mismatch.)

      Parameters:
      s - desired target speed (raw value)
      Returns:
      chosen speed (continuous or discretized) within available range
